3 3. The test must be conducted at least one week before the election. One week before
4 the test is conducted, the county auditor must send the district chairman of each
5 political party having a candidate on the ballot a notice of the test. The notice must
6 state the time, place, and date of the test or tests and that the district chairman or
7 district chairman's designee may attend.
8 4. At the conclusion of the test, the programming for each voting device must be sealed
9 within the device with a unique numbered seal that must be verified by the election
10 inspector before the opening of the polls to make sure the programming has not been
11 removed from the device.
12 5. After each statewide primary, general, and special election, the secretary of state shall
13 order a random testing of the voting system programmingpostelection audit for one
14 precinctpolling location selected randomly in each county of the state according to
15 logic and accuracy testing procedures detailed in subsection 2 and as may be further
16 defined by the. The postelection audit must be commenced on the sixth day following
17 election day and concluded by the eighth day following election day. The county
18 recorder shall deliver to the county auditor the wrapped ballots from the polling
19 location subject to the postelection audit. The secretary of state may further define the
20 procedure for conducting a postelection audit in writing. This test is to be conducted
21 before the meeting of the county canvassing board.
22 6. The county auditor shall appoint an election board consistent with the procedure under
23 section 16.1 - 05 - 01 to conduct the postelection audit. The county auditor shall notice
24 the date, time, and location of the postelection audit. The election board shall review
25 the ballots received under subsection 5 from one federal contest, one statewide
26 contest, one legislative contest if a legislative contest appeared on the ballot, and one
27 county contest. If the election board discovers a discrepancy between the automated
28 tabulating equipment and the results of the postelection audit, the secretary of state
29 may request additional postelection audits within the county, which must serve as the
30 official record used during canvassing.
